Add Basic Auth Strategy Provider and Wire to Controller

This creates a basic authentication strategy using passport-http and a new Provider.  Instead of
running the API unprotected and limiting access to it via AWS security groups, we could use this
module to allow the app (and us, remotely) to interact with the API securely.  The authentication
component is one that the Strongloop team is actively developing but is not production-ready as
of the date of this commit.  Either way, it will pay off later to come up with some sort of AAA strategy
now, even if it's just segmenting away the API to only the front end via layer 3.

Find out more here: 
https://github.com/strongloop/loopback-next/blob/master/packages/authentication/README.md

Add Person Model, Controller, and Repository

This is a more complex way of representing authors on publications or perhaps people in the lab, etc.

Initial Sandbox Heroku Setup, Build, and Deploy

This switches to a setup where each *.datasource.ts pulls in the relavant secret info from an environement variable, removing the need to use travis encrypt-file and pass decrypted files to deploy steps further down the build pipeline.  When using travis encrypt, be sure to always use --pro (travis-ci.com, not .org) and -r owner/repo so that that CLI encrypts with the correct public key.

Heroku Tokens can be read out using with heroku auth:token and encrypted as well.  Heroku only expects yarn.lock OR package-lock.json, not both.  So, if using yarn, delete before deploying or possibly look at using .slugignore? The deply.run option in the heroku deploy (.travis.yml) is not necessary as npm start will be run by default.  Heroku binds the app to a random port internally, as set by process.env.PORT.  So it is necessary to server.bind('rest.port') on that port at runtime. @loopback/build and @loopback/testlab need to be available to heroku so that lb-tsc and lb-mocha can be run when triggered by npm scripts.  

Lastly, removal of travis encrypt-file and other deploy/build options necessitates removal of old files and decryption/un-tarring steps.

Use Decorators To Describe Controller Specification

Upon further reading, the decorators provided by @loopback/rest make describing the API much
more succinct.  The decorators are based on the OpenAPI v3 spec and leverage the controller
metadata/artifacts to fill in the OpenAPI (formerly Swagger) document.

Use OpenAPI Definitition For Controller Metadata

This uses the @api decorator to inject an OpenAPI specification into  the controller.  
This should keep the controller files clear of much of the noise from setting up return types, etc.

(pubmed ID, I think), and pmcid (?).

Add Post Entity and In-Memory Datasource

This creates a simple blog post entity with only a title and body fields.  This will hopefully
demonstrate how the loopback framework works in a basic fashion.  This creates a model
(which defines the a model's properties), a controller (which routes incoming requests to
the appropriate method), and a repository (which provides basic CRUD methods to the
in-memory datasource).  

The in-memory datasource is configured to persist all data into a json file in the ./data
directory.  Be sure to create a data dir andgive it the proper permissions.

commit_list.message:
use millis() and simpler time logging

NTP server is only queried once, in the setup() function.  Also, time is
recorded on the SD card as seconds from Jan 1 1970 UTC.  So, no
formatting and no time zone.  This takes the formatting load off the
Arduino and bugs the NTP server less.

I'm planning on adding a Raspberry Pi web server that will handle
collection, formatting, validation, and Wunderground uploading of the
weather station data.  I'm also planning to add a RTC module to an
Adafruit CC3000 WiFi shield for more reliable time keeping as well as
wireless capabilities.

Initial commit

This sketch uses an Arduino Ethernet Shield to grab the current time
from an NTP server and a DS18B20 digital temperature sensor to measure
the ambient temperature.  It then logs this data into a microSD card on
the shield.
